<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-08-11T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-08-11T17:00:00-05:00" n="729" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d729">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77/1628: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi>
                                    (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Davis</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-08-11T18:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">August
                                            11, 1920—6 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                            <p>862. Department infers that your No. 1143, July 29, 7 p.m. refers to
                                the plan for financing of Chinese Eastern Railway by consortium. Is
                                that correct, and is Department to understand that the French object
                                to that proposal?</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Colby</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>